# Architecture Plan (Issues #1-#21)

## 1) Module Structure and File Organization

### Core app structure (Next.js App Router)
- `app/`
- `app/(public)/layout.tsx` - shared public layout/navigation (#18)
- `app/(public)/page.tsx` - homepage with pagination (#15)
- `app/(public)/posts/[slug]/page.tsx` - post detail (#16)
- `app/(public)/category/[slug]/page.tsx` - category filter page (#17)
- `app/(public)/tag/[slug]/page.tsx` - tag filter page (#17)
- `app/admin/login/page.tsx` - admin login UI (#6)
- `app/admin/page.tsx` - admin dashboard post list (#9)
- `app/admin/posts/new/page.tsx` - create post form (#10)
- `app/admin/posts/[id]/edit/page.tsx` - edit post form (#11)
- `app/admin/categories/page.tsx` - category management (#13)
- `app/admin/tags/page.tsx` - tag management (#14)
- `app/admin/actions.ts` - server actions for CRUD/auth/logout (#8, #10-#14)
- `app/sitemap.ts` and `app/robots.ts` - SEO endpoints (#20)

### Shared libraries
- `lib/db.ts` - Prisma client singleton (#2)
- `lib/auth.ts` - password/session verification helpers (#6-#8)
- `lib/env.ts` - typed environment access/validation (#4)
- `lib/posts.ts` - query helpers for public/admin listing and detail pages (#9, #15-#17)
- `lib/seo.ts` - metadata/Open Graph helpers (#19)
- `lib/pagination.ts` - pagination utilities (#15)

### Components and styles
- `components/admin/*` - admin table/forms/actions
- `components/public/*` - post cards, pagination controls, filters, nav
- `components/shared/*` - reusable UI primitives
- `types/` - shared TypeScript domain types/view models
- `prisma/schema.prisma` and `prisma/seed.ts` (#2, #3)

## 2) Shared Types / Data Model

### Prisma entities
- `Post`: `id`, `title`, `slug`, `content`, `excerpt`, `published`, `publishedAt`, timestamps
- `Category`: `id`, `name`, `slug`
- `Tag`: `id`, `name`, `slug`
- Relations:
- Post -> Category (many-to-one)
- Post <-> Tag (many-to-many)

### TS view types (in `types/`)
- `PostListItem`, `PostDetail`, `CategorySummary`, `TagSummary`, `PaginatedResult<T>`
- Keep UI-facing types separate from raw Prisma models for stability and API clarity.

## 3) Issue Dependency Map

### Foundation first
1. #1 Next.js scaffold
2. #2 Prisma schema + client
3. #4 env configuration
4. #3 seed script (depends on #2)
5. #5 Docker setup (depends on #1/#2/#4)

### Admin auth + management
6. #6 login/password verification (depends on #4)
7. #7 admin route middleware (depends on #6)
8. #8 logout (depends on #6/#7)
9. #9 dashboard list (depends on #2/#7)
10. #10 create post (depends on #2/#7/#9)
11. #11 edit post (depends on #10)
12. #12 delete post (depends on #9/#10/#11)
13. #13 category management (depends on #2/#7)
14. #14 tag management (depends on #2/#7)

### Public site + SEO/docs
15. #15 homepage pagination (depends on #2)
16. #16 post detail (depends on #15)
17. #17 category/tag filters (depends on #13/#14/#15)
18. #18 shared public layout/nav (depends on #15-#17)
19. #19 metadata + OG tags (depends on #15-#18)
20. #20 sitemap + robots (depends on #15-#19)
21. #21 README (depends on all implementation decisions)

## 4) Key Design Decisions

- Use server components by default; client components only for interactive form UX.
- Use Next.js Server Actions for admin CRUD to avoid custom API boilerplate.
- Use cookie-based admin session with middleware guard for `/admin/*` except `/admin/login`.
- Enforce unique slugs for posts/categories/tags and centralize slug generation utility.
- Keep public queries read-optimized in `lib/posts.ts` with explicit `select` fields.
- Keep SEO generation centralized through helper functions reused by page metadata and sitemap.
- SQLite + Prisma chosen for local simplicity; Docker includes persistent volume for DB file.
